Here are the SQL data types, explained clearly and practically (mainly for SQL Server, with notes where others differ).

1. Numeric Data Types
Integer Types
Data Type	Size	Range
TINYINT	1 byte	0 to 255
SMALLINT	2 bytes	-32,768 to 32,767
INT	4 bytes	-2,147,483,648 to 2,147,483,647
BIGINT	8 bytes	-9 quintillion to +9 quintillion
Exact Numeric
Data Type	Description
DECIMAL(p,s) / NUMERIC(p,s)	Fixed precision and scale (recommended for money)
Approximate Numeric
Data Type	Description
FLOAT	Floating-point number
REAL	Less precision than FLOAT

2. Character / String Data Types
Fixed & Variable Length
Data Type	Description
CHAR(n)	Fixed-length string
VARCHAR(n)	Variable-length string
VARCHAR(MAX)	Up to 2 GB text
Unicode (supports Telugu, Hindi, etc.)
Data Type	Description
NCHAR(n)	Fixed-length Unicode
NVARCHAR(n)	Variable-length Unicode
NVARCHAR(MAX)	Large Unicode text

3. Date & Time Data Types
Data Type	Description
DATE	Only date
TIME	Only time
DATETIME	Date + time (old)
DATETIME2	Date + time (recommended)
SMALLDATETIME	Less precision
DATETIMEOFFSET	Date + time + timezone

4. Boolean / Bit
Data Type	Description
BIT	0 or 1 (TRUE/FALSE)

5. Binary Data Types
Data Type	Description
BINARY(n)	Fixed-length binary
VARBINARY(n)	Variable-length binary
VARBINARY(MAX)	Images, files

6. Special / Other Data Types
Data Type	Description
UNIQUEIDENTIFIER	GUID
XML	XML data
JSON	Stored as NVARCHAR (SQL Server)
ROWVERSION	Versioning
SQL_VARIANT	Stores different data types
GEOGRAPHY / GEOMETRY	Spatial data

7. Identity & Auto Increment
id INT IDENTITY(1,1)


Starts at 1

Increments by 1

8. Commonly Used (Best Practice)
Use Case	Recommended Type
Primary Key	INT / BIGINT
Names	NVARCHAR(100)
Description	NVARCHAR(MAX)
Amount	DECIMAL(18,2)
Date & Time	DATETIME2
Boolean	BIT